🌌 Overview
Metasploit: Night Sky Hacker is an interactive, web-based presentation about the Metasploit Framework, designed to engage and educate through a unique cosmic hacker aesthetic. Unlike traditional slide decks, this presentation transforms learning about penetration testing into an immersive experience where information is hidden like stars in the night sky, waiting to be discovered.

🎯 Concept
The core concept revolves around the idea that vulnerabilities are like stars in the night sky – they're always there, but you need to know where to look. Just as ethical hackers probe systems to find weaknesses, users must explore the cosmic interface to reveal information about Metasploit.

Element	Analogy
🌟 Stars	Hidden Metasploit modules (exploits, payloads)
🪐 Central Core	Metasploit Framework itself
☄️ Meteors	Constant activity in the security landscape
📦 Floating Containers	Presentation slides/themed sections
✨ Features
🎨 Visual Features
Realistic Night Sky: Multi-layered starfield with twinkling animation

Galaxy Background: Subtle nebula effects with purple/blue hues

Meteor Showers: Dynamic meteors traveling in multiple directions

Glow Effects: Terminal-style green accents throughout

Floating Animation: All interactive elements gently float

🖱️ Interactive Features
Feature	Interaction	Result
Stars	Hover	Reveals Metasploit module info
Stars	Click	Opens terminal with module details
Core Planet	Hover	Expands and shows Metasploit overview
Core Planet	Click	Opens core system terminal
Slide Containers	Hover	Expands to show full presentation slide
End Button	Click	Shows funny conclusion message
📚 Educational Content
20+ Metasploit modules with real CVE references

5 comprehensive presentation slides

Real terminal commands and outputs

Historical exploit information

Defense strategies

🏗 Technical Architecture
Layered Structure
text
Z-Index Hierarchy:
├── 10000+ → Modals, Terminals
├── 2000   → End Button
├── 1000   → Metasploit Core
├── 500    → Hovered Slides
├── 20-100 → Stars, Slide Containers
├── 15     → Meteors
├── 5-10   → Shooting Stars
├── 1-2    → Background Stars, Galaxy
└── 0      → Base Layer
Key Components
1. Star Background (stars-bg)
css
- Multiple layers of radial gradients
- Random star positions
- Twinkling animation (8s cycle)
- Opacity: 0.7 → 1.0
2. Galaxy Effect
css
- Three overlapping ellipses
- RGBA color overlays
- Blend modes for depth
- Non-interactive layer
3. Metasploit Core
css
Normal State: 40px, subtle glow
Hover State: 250px, bright orange glow
Transition: 0.5s ease
4. Meteor System
javascript
- Random starting positions (5-95%)
- Angles: -75° to +75° (forward directions)
- Distance: 400-1000px
- Speed: 0.5-1.5 seconds
- Size: 60-140px length, 1-3px height
- Frequency: 3-8 meteors per wave
🎮 Interactive Elements
🌟 Stars (20 pieces)
Each star represents a real Metasploit module:

javascript
Data Attributes:
- data-info="exploit/multi/samba/usermap_script"
- CVE references (CVE-2007-2447, CVE-2017-9805, etc.)
- Module types (exploit, payload, auxiliary, post, encoder)
Star Categories:

Type	Example	Purpose
Exploits	eternalblue	Vulnerability exploitation
Payloads	shell_reverse_tcp	Code to run after exploit
Auxiliary	portscan/tcp	Scanning and recon
Post	hashdump	Post-exploitation
Encoders	shikata_ga_nai	AV evasion
🪐 Metasploit Core
The central planet contains:

Framework statistics (2147 exploits, 592 payloads)

Core information

Access to main terminal

📦 Slide Containers (5)
Each container expands to reveal a full presentation slide:

Introduction - What is Metasploit?

Architecture - MSF Components

Basic Commands - msfconsole usage

Famous Exploits - Historical vulnerabilities

Defense - Protection strategies

☄️ Meteor System
The meteor shower creates atmosphere:

Physics: Each meteor has its own trajectory

Variety: Different lengths, speeds, and brightness

Realism: Head flare and fading trail

Frequency: Continuous shower effect

🎯 End Button
A subtle button at the bottom that:

Triggers a humorous conclusion

Shows a "failed exploit" joke

Provides clean exit from presentation

